[3] Germany
Date: Tue 8 Jan 2013
Source: Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI), Germany [summarised, edited]
http://tinyurl.com/c66dsz2


Current Information on Schmallenberg virus (last updated 8 Jan 2013)
-----------------------------------------------------
In Germany animals from 2057 holdings have been tested positive for Schmallenberg virus (SBV) so far [as of 8 Jan 2013] The cases occurred in 1088 cattle holdings, 921 sheep holdings and 48 goat holdings. Affected federal states are North Rhine-Westphalia (272 cattle, 273 sheep, 13 goat holdings), Lower Saxony (226 cattle, 143 sheep, 6 goat holdings), Hesse (124 cattle, 137 sheep holdings, 9 goat holdings), Schleswig-Holstein (111 cattle, 107 sheep holdings, 1 goat holding), Rhineland-Palatinate (1 Bison holding, 50 cattle, 43 sheep, 5 goat holdings), Baden-Wuerttemberg (43 cattle, 35 sheep, 6 goat holdings), Brandenburg (24 cattle, 21 sheep holdings), Thuringia (28 cattle, 42 sheep, 2 goat holdings), Saxony-Anhalt (19 cattle, 23 sheep, 2 goat holdings), Hamburg (2 cattle, 6 sheep holdings), Bavaria (163 cattle, 37 sheep holdings, 1 goat holding), Saxony (11 cattle holdings, 39 sheep holdings), Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania (13 cattle, 11 sheep holdings, 1 goat holding), Saarland (1 cattle holding, 4 sheep, 2 goat holdings) and Berlin (1 sheep holding).

The Netherlands, Belgium, the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Luxembourg, Spain, Denmark , Switzerland, Ireland, Northern Ireland and the Czech Republic have also reported cases of Schmallenberg virus. Austria, Poland, Sweden and Finland detected antibodies in cattle and sheep and goats respevtively. Cattle exported from Austria to Russia also showed SBV-antibodies. In Norway the virus has been detected in biting midges.

[The FLI update -- at the source URL -- includes a detailed table "Confirmed case number on the stocks concerned," 8 Jan 2013, 12.00 h; source: TSN. - Mod.AS]

