[4] Sweden
Date: Mon 7 Jan 2013
Source: Flutrackers [summarised, edited]
http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?t=177873&page=10


A large proportion of Swedish herds have been exposed to infection
-----------------------------------------------------
Schmallenberg virus (SBV), which is spread by midges, has become widely spread in Sweden within a few months. Surveillance Results during autumn 2012 and Map of results based upon bulk milk survey are available at http://tinyurl.com/afwtgdx.

A 1st bulk milk screening was done in May-June 2012, when only one positive herd, located in Blekinge, was detected. In a 2nd bulk milk screening conducted in November [2012], 75 percent of the surveyed herds were found positive for antibodies. The massive spread of SBV in Sweden has occurred between June / July and October 2012.

To evaluate the effects of the virus, 2 types of studies are undertaken:

1. Analysis of fetuses and stillborn animals, to closely study the types of injuries that can be attributed to SBV. There are indications that infection can cause symptoms beyond just malformed offspring. This collection will continue until enough materials are obtained, in order to get a clear picture. This sampling is not done to confirm the SBV in each herd, but to give an idea of the impact the disease has had on fetal development.

2. Several questionnaires are to be distributed to owners, to obtain a more comprehensive picture of the effects of infection on herd level.

Source: SVA (Sweden's National Veterinary Institute)
http://tinyurl.com/a9dnk26.

