[Subsequent to the termination of SBV's vector season of 2012, it remains to be seen what impact the new SBV infections, acquired during the season, will have upon the progeny of domestic and wild ruminants due to be born in the (18) infected European countries during the 1st half of 2013. Obtaining full and accurate data from the farming industry is a demanding task -- conditional for the production of a reliable economical assessment. The data from UK and Sweden, included in items 2 and 4 above, demonstrate the complexity of the issue.

For further reading, subscribers are referred to the presentations addressed at http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/schmallenberg_virus/scientific_seminar_en.htm and to the analysis, by EFSA, of SBV epidemiological data (Nov 2012), reviewed in posting 20121124.1422556.

A recent call for information on the current SBV situation in Hungary is pending. - Mod.AS]
